      <text>Parabola 4 (Master quiz)</text>
    </name>
    <questiontext format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<p>Find the focus and directrix of the parabola \( (c): {@parabola@} \)</p>
<br> 1. a) Rewrite the parabola (c)  in the form \(X^{2} = 4 p Y\).
<br>  \( \quad \) [[input:ans1]] [[validation:ans1]] [[feedback:prt1]]
<br> 2. We recall that in general, \((c): (x-x_{0})^{2}= 4 p (y - y_{0}) \) has focus \(F(x_{0}, y_{0}+p)\) and directrix \((l): y = y_{0}-p\) .
<br>  Find the focus and directrix of the parabola (c). 
<br> Focus: \( F\) ([[input:ans2]], [[input:ans3]])  [[feedback:prtA]]
  <br>  \( \qquad \qquad \)  [[validation:ans2]] \(\qquad\) [[validation:ans3]] 
<br> Directrix \((l):\) [[input:ans4]] [[validation:ans4]] [[feedback:prt4]]]]></text>
    </questiontext>
    <generalfeedback format="html">
      <text><![CDATA[<br><b>Worked solution</b>
<br> 1. a) Rewrite the parabola (c)  in the form \(X^{2} = 4 p Y\).
<br> \( (c): {@parabola@} \)
<br>\(
\begin{array}{rc}
\Leftrightarrow & ({@expr1@})+({@expr2@})= 0 \\ 
\Leftrightarrow &{@(x-aa)^2@}+({@expr2@})= 0 \\ 
\Leftrightarrow & {@(x-aa)^2@}=({@ev(-expr2,simp)@}) \\ 
\Leftrightarrow & {@(x-aa)^2@}= 4 \cdot ({@pp@})({@y-cc@}) 
\end{array}
\)
<br> So, \( X = {@x-aa@}\), \(p={@pp@} \) and \( Y = {@y-cc@} \).
<br> 2.  Find the focus and directrix of the parabola (c). 
<br>In general, \((c): (x-x_{0})^{2}= 4 p (y - y_{0}) \) has focus \(F(x_{0}, y_{0}+p)\) and directrix \((l): y = y_{0}-p\) 
<br> It follows that \(y_{0} = {@cc@} \),  \( x_{0}= {@aa@} \) and \(p={@pp@}\).
<br> Therefore, Focus: \(F({@aa@},{@cc+pp@}) \equiv ({@aa@},{@ev(cc+pp,simp)@}) \) and directrix \( (l): y = {@cc-pp@}= {@ev(cc-pp,simp)@}\)]]></text>
    </generalfeedback>
